<a id='GBS.PA63.w.1.7.0'></a><p class='gtxt_body' style='font-size:102%;text-indent:1em;' id='para.76.1.7.box.218.1888.1293.84.q.60'>4 Blessed <span style='font-style:italic;'>are </span>they tliat dwell in thy house: they will be still praising thee. Selah.</p>
<a id='GBS.PA63.w.1.8.0'></a><p class='gtxt_body' style='font-size:102%;text-indent:1em;' id='para.76.1.8.box.218.1990.1295.356.q.60'>1. <span style='font-style:italic;'>&quot;How </span><span style='font-style:italic;'>amiable,&quot; </span>or, How <span style='font-style:italic;'>bmcly</span><span style='font-style:italic;'>! </span>He does not tell us how lovely they were, because he could not. His expressions show us that his feelings were inexpressible. Lovely to the memory, to the mind, to the heart, to the eye, to the whole soul, are the assemblies of the saints. Earth contains no sight so refreshing to us as the gathering of believers for worship. Those are sorry saints who see nothing amiable in the services of the Lord&#39;s house. <span style='font-style:italic;'>&quot;Are </span><span style='font-style:italic;'>thy </span><span style='font-style:italic;'>tabernacles.</span>&quot; The tabernacle had been pitched in several places, and, moreover, was divided into several courts and portions; hence, probably, the plural number is here used. It was all and altogether lovely to David. Outer court, or inner court, he loved every portion of it. Every cord and curtain was dear<a id='GBS.PA64.w.1.0.0'></a><span class='gtxt_body' id='para.77.1.0.box.279.263.1295.347.q.60'>
to him. Even when at a distance, he rejoiced to remember the sacred tent where Jehovah revealed himself, and he cried out with exultation while he pictured in fond imagination its sacred services, and solemn rites, as he had seen them in bygone times. Because they are <span style='font-style:italic;'>thy </span>tabernacles, <span style='font-style:italic;'>&quot;0 </span><span style='font-style:italic;'>Lord </span><span style='font-style:italic;'>of </span><span style='font-style:italic;'>hosts,&quot; </span>therefore arc they so dear to thy people. Thy pavilion is the centre of the camp, around which all thy creatures gather, and towards which their eyes are turned, as armies look to the tent of the king. Thou rulest all the companies of creatures with such goodness, that all their hosts rejoice in thy dwelling-place, and the bands of thy saints especially hail thee with joyful loyalty as Jehovah of hosts.</span></p>
